-- ─── 1. Rule system overview ───────────────────────────────────────────────
DECLARE @bRulesOverview NVARCHAR(MAX) = N'MegaForm has a runtime rule engine that mutates the form DOM whenever any input fires `change` or `input`. Rules live in `schema.settings.rules` as an array of Rule Definitions. Each definition has a WHEN condition tree, a THEN action list (applied when the tree evaluates true), and an ELSE action list (applied when false). Rules are sorted by `priority` ascending, then evaluated top-to-bottom.

Files of record:
- MegaForm.UI/src/builder/rule-engine.ts        — pure JS evaluator (compare, evaluateNode, collectEffects, applyEffects)
- MegaForm.UI/src/builder/rule-builder-ui.ts    — visual rule editor (Rules tab)
- MegaForm.UI/src/renderer/conditional.ts       — runtime binding (listens to change/input and re-runs evaluateRules)

What rules CAN do (built-in):
- Show/Hide a field, section, or step
- Require/Optional a field, section, or step (toggles required validation)
- Enable/Disable a field, section, or step (toggles disabled attribute)
- SetValue (write a string into a field) / Clear (wipe a field)

What rules CAN NOT do (gaps — use workarounds below):
- Auto-CALCULATE sums (no formula action). Workarounds:
  * Use DataGrid widget with `computeFormula` per column + `totalFormula` (see form_pattern-formula-datagrid)
  * For non-line-item totals, populate the visible total via SetValue once a single trigger field changes — only works for static math the AI can pre-bake into the rule chain.
  * For arbitrary calc, use DynamicLabel + SQL or a script token.
- No "if any field in a group changes" trigger: rules listen to any input event globally.
- No async/server-side conditions.

Rule definition shape (canonical):
```json
{
  "id": "definition_<random>",
  "name": "Rule 1",
  "enabled": true,
  "priority": 1,
  "when": {
    "id": "group_<random>", "type": "group", "logic": "all",
    "children": [
      { "id": "rule_<r>", "type": "rule", "field": "gender", "operator": "eq", "value": "Male" }
    ]
  },
  "then": [
    { "id": "action_<r>", "action": "show",    "targetType": "field",   "target": "veteran_status" }
  ],
  "else": [
    { "id": "action_<r>", "action": "hide",    "targetType": "field",   "target": "veteran_status" }
  ]
}
```

When the AI is asked to ADD a rule, it should:
1. Read the current `schema.settings.rules` array (or create []).
2. Append a new Rule Definition object using exactly the shape above. (IDs can be any unique strings; the renderer accepts arbitrary slugs.)
3. Emit set_form_meta with `rules` as a top-level array OR replace_form_schema with settings.rules patched.
4. Always set `enabled:true` + `priority` (default 1).';

